{"title_page": "Government of Uttar Pradesh", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}{{Infobox Indian state government\n|name_of_state= Uttar Pradesh\n|coat_of_arms= Seal of Uttar Pradesh.svg\n<!--Government-->\n|high_court    = [[Allahabad High Court]]\n|legislative_assembly= [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n|speaker= [[Hriday Narayan Dikshit]] ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]])\n|dpy_speaker= \n|member_in_assembly= 404 (403 elected + 1 nominated)\n|legislative_council= [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council]]\n|chairman= [[Ramesh Yadav]] ([[Samajwadi Party|SP]])\n|member_in_council= 100\n|chief_justice= Justice [[Govind Mathur]]\n|seat_of_government= [[Lucknow]]\n|name_of_governor= [[Anandiben Patel]] <ref name=\"Governor of UP\">{{cite web |title= The Governor of Uttar Pradesh |url= http://uplegisassembly.gov.in/ENGLISH/governor_current.htm |website= uplegisassembly.gov.in |publisher= Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly |accessdate= 12 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170503081924/http://uplegisassembly.gov.in/ENGLISH/governor_current.htm |archive-date= 3 May 2017 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n|name_of_chief_minister= [[Yogi Adityanath]] ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]])\n| website                 = {{URL|www.upgov.nic.in|Official Website}}\n|name_of_dpy_chief_minister=[[Keshav Prasad Maurya]] ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]]) <br />Dr. [[Dinesh Sharma]] ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]])\n|chief_secretary =[[Rajendra Kumar Tiwari]], [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]\n|Chairman,Board_of_Revenue =[[Deepak Trivedi]], [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]\n\n|Chairman , Board of Revenue=[[Deepak Trivedi]], [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]}}\n\nThe '''Government of Uttar Pradesh''' is a democratically elected state government in the [[India]]n state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] with the [[governor]] as its appointed constitutional head of the state by the [[President of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upgovernor.gov.in/upgovernor.gov.in/roleofgov.htm|title=Role of The Governor|website=upgovernor.gov.in|publisher=Raj Bhavan Uttar Pradesh|accessdate=17 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407230227/http://www.upgovernor.gov.in/upgovernor.gov.in/roleofgov.htm|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[List of governors of Uttar Pradesh|Governor of Uttar Pradesh]] is appointed for a period of five years and appoints the chief minister and his or her council of ministers, who are vested with the executive powers of the state. The governor remains a ceremonial head of the state, while the chief minister and his or her council are responsible for day-to-day government functions. The state of Uttar Pradesh's influence on Indian politics is important, and often paramount and/or a [[bellwether]], as it sends the largest number of [[Member of parliament (India)|members of parliament]] to both the [[Lok Sabha]] and the [[Rajya Sabha]], the state's population being more than 200 million; approximately double that of the next-most populous state.\n\n==Legislature==\n{{Main|Uttar Pradesh Legislature (Vidhan Bhawan)|Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council}}\nThe state is governed by a [[parliamentary system]] of [[representative democracy]]. Uttar Pradesh is one of the seven states in India, where the state legislature is bicameral, comprising two houses: the [[Vidhan Sabha]] (legislative assembly) and the [[Vidhan Parishad]] (legislative council).<ref name=\"vidhan parishad\">{{cite web|url=http://legislativebodiesinindia.nic.in/UttarPradesh-LC.htm|title=Uttar Pradesh Vidhan Parishad structure|website=Legislative Bodies of India|publisher=[[Government of India]]|accessdate=19 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417175655/http://legislativebodiesinindia.nic.in/UttarPradesh-LC.htm|archive-date=17 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Vidhan Sabha\">{{cite web|url=http://legislativebodiesinindia.nic.in/UTTAR%20PRADESH.htm|title=Uttar Pradesh Vidhan Sabha structure|website=Legislative Bodies of India|publisher=[[Government of India]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417175232/http://legislativebodiesinindia.nic.in/UTTAR%20PRADESH.htm|archive-date=17 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] consists of 404 members who are elected for five-year terms. The [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council]] is a permanent body of 100 members with one-third (33 members) retiring every two years. Since Uttar Pradesh sends the largest number of legislators to the national Parliament, it is often considered to be one of the most important states with respect to Indian politics.<ref name=\"elections\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/02/2012286478579763.html|title=Legislative elections in Uttar Pradesh|last=Four other states seen as barometer of support for federal government.|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref> The state contributes 80 seats to the lower house of the [[Parliament of India]], the [[Lok Sabha]] and 31 seats to the upper house, the [[Rajya Sabha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://164.100.47.5/Newmembers/memberstatewise.aspx|title=Statewise List|date=|publisher=164.100.47.5|accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/faq/freaq1.asp|title=Rajya Sabha|publisher=Rajya Sabha|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130724045633/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/faq/freaq1.asp|archivedate=24 July 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-07-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Grover1989\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fRqrO0Hx0Y0C&pg=PA37|title=Legislative Council in State Legislatures|author=Verinder Grover|publisher=Deep & Deep Publications|isbn=978-81-7100-193-4|pages=37\u2013255|accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-2.pdf|title=Composition of Rajya Sabha|work=Rajya Sabha|publisher=Rajya Sabha Secretariat|location=New Delhi|pages=24\u201325|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305020442/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-2.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016|url-status=dead|accessdate=15 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Executive==\nThe government is headed by the governor who appoints the chief minister and his or her council of ministers. The governor is appointed for a period of five years and acts as the constitutional head of the state. The governor remains the ceremonial head of the state with the day-to-day running of the government is taken care of by the chief minister and his or her council of ministers in whom a great deal of legislative powers is vested.\n\nThe council of ministers consists of cabinet ministers and ministers of state. The Secretariat headed by the [[Chief secretary (India)|chief secretary]] assists the council of ministers.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|title=CONSTITUTIONAL SETUP|website=Government of Uttar Pradesh|url-status=live|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":64\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill Education]]|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=4.1\u20134.5}}</ref> The chief secretary is also the administrative head of the government.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":64\" />\n\nEach government department is headed by a Minister, who is assisted by an [[Additional Chief Secretary|additional chief secretary]] or a [[Principal secretary (India)|principal secretary]], who usually is an officer of [[Indian Administrative Service]], the additional chief secretary or principal secretary serves as the administrative head of the department they are assigned to.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":64\" /> Each department also has officers of the rank of secretary, special secretary, joint secretary etc. assisting the minister and the [[additional chief secretary]] or [[Principal secretary (India)|principal secretary]].<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":64\" />\n\n=== Council of ministers ===\n<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://information.up.nic.in/Module_View.aspx?id_view=270|title=\u0915\u0948\u092c\u093f\u0928\u0947\u091f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940|website=Government of Uttar Pradesh|trans-title=Cabinet Ministers|url-status=live|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://upcmo.up.nic.in/cabinet_minister.htm|title=Cabinet Ministers|website=[[Uttar Pradesh]] CMO|publisher=[[Uttar Pradesh Government]]|access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://information.up.nic.in/Module_View.aspx?id_view=269|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 (\u0938\u094d\u0935\u0924\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092d\u093e\u0930)|website=Government of Uttar Pradesh|trans-title=State Ministers (Independent Charge)|url-status=live|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://upcmo.up.nic.in/state_minister_ic.htm|title=Ministers Of State (Independent Charge)|website=[[Uttar Pradesh]] CMO|publisher=[[Uttar Pradesh Government]]|access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://information.up.nic.in/Module_View.aspx?id_view=268|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940|website=Government of Uttar Pradesh|trans-title=State Ministers|url-status=live|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://upcmo.up.nic.in/state_minister.htm|title=State Ministers|website=[[Uttar Pradesh]] CMO|publisher=[[Uttar Pradesh Government]]|access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+Council of ministers of the Government of Uttar Pradesh<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n!S.No.\n!Name of Minister\n!Ra