 and union territories. 28. Uttar Pradesh|author1=Gopal K. Bhargava|first=|author2=Shankarlal C. Bhatt|publisher=Gyan Books Pvt Ltd|year=2005|isbn=978-81-7835-384-5|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=31\u201333|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref> Other judges are appointed by the President of India on the advice of the Chief Justice of the High Court.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\"courts\" /> ''Subordinate Judicial Service'', categorized into two divisions viz. Uttar Pradesh civil judicial services and Uttar Pradesh higher judicial service is another vital part of the judiciary of Uttar Pradesh.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\"BhargavaBhatt2005\" /> While the Uttar Pradesh civil judicial services comprise the Civil Judges (Junior Division)/Judicial Magistrates and civil judges (Senior Division)/Chief Judicial Magistrate, the Uttar Pradesh higher judicial service comprises civil and sessions judges.<ref name=\":23\" /> The Subordinate Judicial Service (viz. The district court of [[Etawah]] and the district court of Kanpur Dehat) of the judiciary at Uttar Pradesh is controlled by the District Judge.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\"BhargavaBhatt2005\" /><ref name=\"Civil Judiciary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allahabadhighcourt.in/event/TheHistoryRoleSubordinateJudiciaryBBPrasad.pdf|title=Subordinate Civil Judiciary in Uttar Pradesh|publisher=[[Allahabad High Court]]|accessdate=19 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n{{See also|Divisions of Uttar Pradesh|Districts of Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n=== Divisional administration ===\nThe Indian state of Uttar Pradesh is made up of 75 administrative districts, that are grouped into 18 [[Administrative divisions of Uttar Pradesh|divisions]]. Each division consists of 3-7 districts. A [[Divisional commissioner (India)|divisional commissioner]], an officer of the [[Indian Administrative Service]] (IAS) is responsible for heading the administration of a division, the Divisional Commissioner is also responsible for the collection of revenue and maintenance of law and order in his or her division.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|title=Constitutional Setup|website=Government of Uttar Pradesh|url-status=live|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration (6th Edition)|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=563\u2013572}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=26\u2013129}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=5.1\u20135.2}}</ref>\n\nThere are also eight police zones and eighteen police ranges in the state. Each zone consists of 2-3 ranges and is headed by an [[Additional director general of police|additional director general]]-ranked officer of the [[Indian Police Service]] (IPS). Whereas a range consists of three to four districts and is headed by an [[Inspector-general of police|inspector general]]-ranked or a [[Deputy inspector general of police|deputy inspector general]]-ranked IPS officer.\n\n===District administration===\nA district of an Indian state is an administrative geographical unit, headed by a [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]] (DM), an IAS officer. The district magistrate is responsible for coordinating the work between various departments in the district, is responsible for law and order in the district and is also given the power of an executive magistrate. The DM is assisted by a number of officers belonging to the [[Provincial Civil Service (Uttar Pradesh)|Provincial Civil Service]] and other state services.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration (6th Edition)|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=573\u2013597}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=6.1\u20136.6}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=50\u2013124}}</ref>\n\nA [[Superintendent of police (India)|senior superintendent of police]] or superintendent of police, a gazetted officer (PPS or IPS in case of SP and IPS in case of SSP) of Uttar Pradesh Cadre, is entrusted with the responsibility of maintaining law and order and related issues of the district. He or she is assisted by other junior to SSP/SP rank IPS and PPS gazetted officers in addition to Uttar Pradesh Police non-gazetted officials.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nA divisional forest officer, an officer belonging to the [[Indian Forest Service]], in the rank of [[Deputy Conservator of Forests|deputy conservator of forests]], is responsible for managing the forests, the environment, and wildlife-related issues of the district with the assistance of the Uttar Pradesh Forest Service.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nSectoral development is looked after by the district head of each development department such as public works, health, education, agriculture, [[animal husbandry]], etc. These officers belong to the various state services. These officers have to report to the DM of the district.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Politics==\nUttar Pradesh politics is dominated by the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], the [[Samajwadi Party]] and the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] (BSP) as the third major party. The Bharatiya Janata Party occupies the current government headed by Chief Minister [[Yogi Adityanath]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Governors of Uttar Pradesh]]\n* [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Indian Administration (6th Edition)|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill Education]]|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://up.gov.in/ Official Website of Government of Uttar Pradesh]\n*[http://uphome.gov.in/ Official Website of Department of Home of Government of Uttar Pradesh]\n*[http://www.uptourism.gov.in/ Official Website of Department of Tourism of Government of Uttar Pradesh]\n\n{{Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Government of India by state or territory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Government Of Uttar Pradesh}}\n[[Category:1829 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Government of Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "88.208.39.74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added position of senior IAS officer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_of_Uttar_Pradesh"}
